<%- include('../../partials/implementer-core.md.ejs', { specificsBlock: `## Go Specifics

### Error Handling
- Return \`error\` as the last return value; never panic except in \`main\` or \`init\` for unrecoverable state.
- Wrap errors with \`fmt.Errorf("context: %w", err)\` to preserve the chain; use \`errors.Is\` / \`errors.As\` to inspect.
- Define sentinel errors as \`var ErrFoo = errors.New("foo")\` at package level — never compare error strings.

### Context Plumbing
- Accept \`context.Context\` as the first parameter of every function that does I/O or blocking work.
- Never store contexts in structs — pass them as arguments.
- Respect cancellation: check \`ctx.Err()\` after blocking calls.

### Testing
- Run the suite with \`go test ./...\`; gate CI on \`go test -race ./...\`.
- Use table-driven tests with \`[]struct{ name, input, want }\` slices and \`t.Run(tc.name, ...)\`.
- Use \`t.Helper()\` in assertion helpers to surface correct file/line numbers.
- Prefer \`testify/require\` for fatal assertions and \`testify/assert\` for non-fatal.

### Anti-patterns to avoid
- Never use \`interface{}\` when a concrete type or typed interface suffices.
- Never ignore returned \`error\` values — use \`_\` only when truly intentional and comment why.
- Never use \`init()\` for side effects that depend on external state.
- Never use goroutines without a clear lifetime owner (use \`errgroup\` for fan-out).
- Never copy a \`sync.Mutex\` — always pass by pointer.` }) %>
